SIMPLE: mistake
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mistake
<hw>Mis*take"</hw> <pr>(m⟦icr⟧s*t⟦amac⟧k")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & obs. p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mistook</conjf>
<pr>(m⟦icr⟧s*t⟦oocr⟧k")</pr>; <pos>p. p.</pos> <conjf>Mistaken</conjf>
<pr>(m⟦icr⟧s*t⟦amac⟧k"'n)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Mistaking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Pref. <ets>mis-</ets> +
<ets>take</ets>: cf. Icel. <ets>mistaka</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To take or choose wrongly.</def> <mark>[Obs. or R.]</mark>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To take in a wrong sense; to misunderstand
misapprehend, or misconceive; <as>as, to <ex>mistake</ex> a remark; to
<ex>mistake</ex> one's meaning.</as></def> <rj><au>Locke.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My father's purposes have been <qex>mistook</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To substitute in thought or perception; <as>as, to
<ex>mistake</ex> one person for another</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A man may <qex>mistake</qex> the love of virtue for the practice
of it.</q> <rj><qau>Johnson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To have a wrong idea of in respect of character,
qualities, etc.; to misjudge.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Mistake</qex> me not so much,⟦br⟧
To think my poverty is treacherous.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistake</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Mistake
<hw>Mis*take"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To err in knowledge,
perception, opinion, or judgment; to commit an unintentional
error.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Servants <qex>mistake</qex>, and sometimes occasion
misunderstanding among friends.</q> <rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 932 --></p>

<p><ent>Mistake</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Mistake
<hw>Mis*take"</hw> <pr>(m⟦icr⟧s*t⟦amac⟧k")</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>An apprehending wrongly; a misconception; a
misunderstanding; a fault in opinion or judgment; an unintentional error
of conduct.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Infallibility is an absolute security of the understanding from
all possibility of <qex>mistake</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Tillotson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>Misconception, error, which when
non-negligent may be ground for rescinding a contract, or for refusing
to perform it.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>No mistake</b></col>, <cd>surely; without fail; <as>as,
it will happen at the appointed time, and <ex>no mistake</ex></as>.</cd>
<mark>[Low]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Blunder; error; bull. See
<er>Blunder</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mistaken</ent>⟦br⟧
